The study of rules governing language particular to contexts. For example, "true" means accurately representing the world. However, if at a press conference a reporter were to ask "Is it true you plan on invading Iraq" instead of just asking "Are you planning on invading Iraq?", the word "true" in the first sentence functions to suggest there are rumors already in existence regarding an invasion. This has little to do with the semantic meaning of the word true, but in the context of the situation the term operates differently then its meaning suggests. Such phenomena are the subject matter of pragmatics.